e-class families. &#10;The mistake in this case is that the social workers failed to follow up. It was a welfare problem, not an education one,so the social workers should have used the powers they already have to gain access to the children. There's no point in creating new laws if the ones we've already got aren't used properly. Educate the social workers and provide them with adequate resources and support, which would achieve much better results than requiring social workers to visit 50,000 children who don't need attention, diverting it away from the few who do. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="877" language="en" documentId="1060" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Thienz" date="28 July 2010 9:52pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6869835" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="42" thumbsDown="0" origId="1060" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="325"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="326" end="877"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>